<h2>The Short Answer: Yes, With Important Nuances</h2>
<p>Psychotherapy is one of the most extensively studied interventions in medicine. Thousands of randomised controlled trials, systematic reviews, and meta-analyses have examined its effectiveness across conditions, populations, and modalities. The cumulative conclusion is clear: therapy works significantly better than no treatment for a wide range of mental health conditions.</p>

<p>The landmark 1977 meta-analysis by Smith and Glass examined 375 studies and found that the average therapy recipient was better off than 80% of control participants. Subsequent meta-analyses have largely confirmed and extended this finding. For conditions like depression, anxiety disorders, PTSD, OCD, and eating disorders, specific therapy approaches produce strong, well-documented outcomes.</p>

<h2>Effect Sizes: What the Numbers Mean</h2>
<p>Research uses "effect sizes" to quantify treatment impact. In psychotherapy research:</p>
<ul>
  <li>CBT for depression: effect size ~0.87 (large — similar to antidepressant medication)</li>
  <li>CBT for anxiety disorders: effect size ~1.0 (large)</li>
  <li>Exposure therapy for specific phobias: effect size ~1.5+ (very large)</li>
  <li>EMDR for PTSD: effect size comparable to trauma-focused CBT</li>
  <li>DBT for BPD: strong evidence for reducing suicidal behaviour, self-harm, and hospitalisation</li>
</ul>

<p>An effect size of 0.8 is considered large in psychological research — similar to the effect of antihypertensives on blood pressure.</p>

<h2>When Therapy Works Best</h2>
<p>Several factors predict better therapy outcomes:</p>

<p><strong>Evidence-based match:</strong> Using an approach with demonstrated evidence for the specific condition. CBT for panic disorder outperforms supportive counselling. ERP for OCD outperforms standard anxiety therapy. The match matters.</p>

<p><strong>Therapeutic alliance:</strong> The quality of the relationship between client and therapist consistently predicts outcomes across all therapy types. A good alliance is not just pleasant — it is mechanistically important.</p>

<p><strong>Client readiness and engagement:</strong> Clients who are actively engaged, complete between-session work, and are ready to change consistently do better. Therapy is participatory, not passive.</p>

<p><strong>Feedback and measurement:</strong> Therapists who routinely measure outcomes and adjust based on the data produce better results than those who don't. This is well-established in research.</p>

<h2>When Therapy Doesn't Work</h2>
<p>Therapy underperforms when:</p>
<ul>
  <li>The wrong approach is used for the condition (a non-specific supportive therapy for OCD, for example)</li>
  <li>The therapeutic alliance is poor and not addressed</li>
  <li>The therapist lacks training in the appropriate approach</li>
  <li>The client has a co-occurring condition (e.g., active substance use) that needs to be addressed first</li>
  <li>The severity requires a different level of care than outpatient therapy</li>
</ul>

<p>Therapy "not working" is frequently a mismatch between the treatment and what's needed — not evidence that therapy in general doesn't work.</p>

<h2>Online vs In-Person: Does the Modality Matter?</h2>
<p>Research increasingly shows no significant difference in outcomes between online and in-person therapy for most conditions. Multiple meta-analyses confirm equivalent efficacy. The modality affects access, convenience, and preferences — but not, for most people, the effectiveness of treatment.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>How quickly should I see results?</strong><br/>
Research suggests that clients who will respond to therapy typically show some improvement within the first 4–8 sessions. If there's no improvement after 10–12 sessions, the approach or therapist fit may need to be reconsidered.</p>

<p><strong>Is therapy better than medication?</strong><br/>
It depends on the condition. For depression and anxiety, therapy and medication produce similar outcomes; therapy shows more durable effects after treatment ends. For some conditions (psychosis, bipolar disorder, severe OCD), medication is an important component alongside therapy. For most conditions, the combination outperforms either alone.</p>

<p><strong>Does therapy last? Or will symptoms come back?</strong><br/>
Well-conducted CBT and other evidence-based therapies show durable effects in follow-up studies. Clients learn skills they retain. Relapse is possible but often less severe, and clients know what to do. "Booster" sessions can help during stressful periods.</p>

